    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1e923982_57e44a23",
        "filename": "android/android-emu/android/base/AlignedBuf.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 101,
      "author": {
        "id": 1080076
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-07-10T00:00:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/types/max_align_t\n\u003e\u003ePointers returned by allocation functions such as std::malloc are suitably aligned for any object, which means they are aligned at least as strict as std::max_align_t.\n\u003e\u003estd::max_align_t is usually synonymous with the largest scalar type, which is long double on most platforms, and its alignment requirement is either 8 or 16.\n\nthis means any dynamic allocation is aligned at least to 8 bytes. There are no 4 byte alignments on x64 systems at all",
      "parentUuid": "b0e1f7a8_6a2dc8d4",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 101,
        "startChar": 44,
        "endLine": 101,
        "endChar": 51
      },
